{"source_key":"sha256-b4cec238995b260ac54aae4fdce1a71d","record_index":137,"record_hash":"sha256:13ca423793e7b84283f1f01504296365df391660944c11a67d17975560b8e4c8","timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:06:51.495Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_kind":"file_edit","file_path_hashes":["6c16e3406f4fbd24452fca27625d018c"],"tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: etc/plans/agentlog-local-publishing.md\n+# Agentlog Local-First Publishing\n+\n+## Intent\n+\n+Make `but-agentlog` private by default.\n+\n+Captured agent sessions should stay local unless the user explicitly publishes\n+them. A reviewer-facing Agent Trail page should only exist for metadata the user\n+has chosen to share, or for users who have opted into sharing agentlogs by\n+default.\n+\n+## Why\n+\n+Today capture and publish are effectively coupled. The agent hook records a\n+session, then `but-agentlog` silently runs metadata sync. That means a user who\n+has GitMeta sync configured can publish every captured agentlog without taking a\n+separate sharing action.\n+\n+That is too leaky for normal work. A user may be:\n+\n+- exploring private customer metrics or internal stats on a public repository\n+- using an agent for sensitive investigation before deciding what belongs in a PR\n+- not ready to share a branch's agent context yet\n+- philosophically fine with local capture but not automatic propagation\n+\n+The safer default is local-first capture plus explicit publish.\n+\n+## Current Shape\n+\n+Relevant `git-meta` change:\n+\n+- `[REDACTED:path]` commit `4c03a95` (`Use local prefix for unshared metadata`)\n+- `git-meta-lib` now treats `local:` as a hard serialization exclusion.\n+- The check happens before user filter rules, so even a rule like\n+  `route local:** private` cannot serialize `local:` keys.\n+- This applies to every target and to values/tombstones that pass through\n+  serialization.\n+\n+Relevant `but-agentlog` shape:\n+\n+- Capture writes project-scoped GitMeta keys like:\n+  - `gitbutler:agent-sessions`\n+  - `gitbutler:agent-session:<session>:...`\n+  - `gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:<target-kind>:<target-hash>`\n+- The hook path records the transcript and then spawns `but agentlog sync`.\n+- `skim`, `show`, and the Agent Trail projection read those same project-scoped\n+  keys.\n+- Agent Trail fetches public `refs/meta/main`, materializes it, then calls the\n+  `but-agentlog` projection API. Its v1 contract treats public `refs/meta/main`\n+  as already-published metadata.\n+\n+Consequence: as long as agentlog keys are written without `local:`, sync can make\n+them visible to Agent Trail.\n+\n+## Product Needs\n+\n+Default capture should write agentlog data under `local:`.\n+\n+The obvious key mapping is:\n+\n+```text\n+local:gitbutler:agent-session:...\n+local:gitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:...\n+```\n+\n+Publishing removes only the leading `local:` and preserves the current public key\n+shape. That keeps Agent Trail and other public readers on the existing published\n+contract.\n+\n+Users need a command that publishes agentlog data for a target:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog publish branch <branch>\n+but agentlog publish review <review-or-pr>\n+but agentlog publish change <change>\n+```\n+\n+The command should:\n+\n+- find the relevant local sessions and turns for that target, using the same\n+  relationship logic that powers `skim` and Agent Trail\n+- include the supporting session metadata required for those turns to render\n+  correctly\n+- move the relevant keys from `local:gitbutler:...` to `gitbutler:...`\n+- run metadata sync after a successful publish\n+- support `--dry-run`, printing what would be shared without changing metadata or\n+  syncing\n+\n+Users who want old behavior should have an explicit opt-in. Start minimal: a CLI\n+flag or config setting is enough. The important bit is that sharing-by-default is\n+visible and intentional.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+Do not make Agent Trail read local metadata.\n+\n+Do not make users select individual GitMeta keys. The unit of intent is branch,\n+review, or change, not storage plumbing.\n+\n+Do not design a full privacy policy system here. `local:` is a publication guard,\n+not encryption, access control, or a guarantee that captured local data is\n+appropriate to share.\n+\n+Do not overfit the storage design before implementation. The task is to preserve\n+the current public shape while adding a local-first staging step.\n+\n+## Engineering Notes\n+\n+The main upstream dependency is already in place: `git-meta-lib` can keep\n+`local:` keys out of serialized refs.\n+\n+The main `but-agentlog` change is behavioral:\n+\n+- write captured data under `local:` by default\n+- teach local reads/publish discovery to look at local agentlog indexes\n+- keep published reads compatible with the existing `gitbutler:agentlog-*` keys\n+- make `agentlog sync` harmless for unpublished captures\n+\n+Publishing should not become an O(total metadata) operation if we can avoid it.\n+If moving `local:gitbutler:...` to `gitbutler:...` needs a bulk prefix-rename or\n+atomic set-and-remove primitive, fix that in `[REDACTED:path]` rather\n+than papering over it downstream.\n+\n+Agent Trail likely does not need changes if published keys keep the current\n+shape. It should continue to consume only materialized public metadata from\n+`refs/meta/main`.\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Should `publish` move local data or copy it and leave a local copy behind? I\n+  would pick move first: it matches the user's mental model and avoids duplicate\n+  reads.\n+- For a target match, do we publish entire sessions that touched the target, or\n+  only the matching turns plus enough context to render them? Entire sessions are\n+  simpler and less likely to produce broken context; turn-scoped publishing leaks\n+  less.\n+- Should local `skim` show local-only sessions, published sessions, or both? For\n+  day-to-day agent context, both is probably right, with a clear published/local\n+  status.\n+- Where should the share-by-default preference live first: hook flag, Git config,\n+  or GitMeta config? A hook flag is the smallest start; config is nicer once the\n+  behavior stabilizes.\n+- How should `--dry-run` report scale: key count, session count, turn count,\n+  target names, or all of the above?\n+- What migration story do we want for existing already-published agentlogs? The\n+  safest default is to leave them published and only apply local-first behavior to\n+  new captures.\n+- Does `git-meta-lib` need an atomic `MetaEdit::Remove` or prefix-move API before\n+  this is pleasant and safe to implement?\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:06:51.495Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}